    {
      "ESSeqNum": 0,
      "FacilityID": 1000106220,
      "SummaryText": "Executive Summary:\n1. The accidental release prevention and emergency response policies at the facility:\nThe Linde Gas & Equipment - Indianapolis (LG&E) located in Indianapolis, Indiana complies with USEPA's accident prevention rule, and it is our policy to adhere to all applicable federal, state, and local laws. LG&E is committed to operating in a safe and environmentally sound manner and being responsible member of the community by making safety information available to the community. Safety is a top priority at LG&E as reflected in its proactive planning, state-of-the art equipment, employee training and its coordination with external agency to prevent accidental releases from occurring and instituting controls to rapidly mitigate a potential release if it does occur. \n\n2. A description of the facility and the regulated substances handled:\nThe Linde Gas & Equipment \u0096 Indianapolis is an industrial and specialty gas plant that uses, manufactures, or stores a chemical listed in part 68 of Title 40 of the Code of Federal Regulations. Acetylene and Propylene are stored in quantities exceeding the applicable threshold quantities, as established by the EPA. The processes involving Acetylene is production, cylinder filling and distribution. The process involving Propylene is a redistribution (trans fill) operation.\n\n3. The general accidental release prevention program:\nIn accordance with OSHA\u0092s Process Safety Management standard and EPA\u0092s Risk Management Program rule, the Linde Gas & Equipment - Indianapolis has a comprehensive accident prevention program in place. This program is built around process safety concepts such as:\n - Technical documentation of Process Safety Information, describing the physical properties of the hazardous substances, the safety systems in place to control these substances, and the critical operating parameters of the associated equipment and systems.\n- Procedures and programs to develop, maintain, and control key program elements such as proc"
